#compdef grpc-federation-generator
# ============================================================================
# grpc-federation-generator - Generate federated-gRPC server stub from a
#                              Protocol Buffers schema with grpc-federation
#                              custom options (Go, MIT)
#
# Author : Mercari (mercari organization)
# Upstream: https://github.com/mercari/grpc-federation
#
# `grpc-federation` is Mercari's framework that compiles a
# Protocol Buffers schema decorated with custom options into a
# *federation-layer* gRPC server in Go - the BFF / GraphQL-
# style "stitch together multiple backend services into one
# response" pattern, but expressed in protobuf instead of a
# new DSL. Each federation message declares its sources (other
# gRPC services, REST endpoints, embedded values) + the
# fields-to-fetch chain; `grpc-federation-generator` walks
# the declaration graph + emits a single Go service stub that
# parallelizes the upstream calls + assembles the response.
#
# Usage:
#   grpc-federation-generator [options] [<proto_path>]
#
# Flags (jessevdk/go-flags - GNU-style):
#   -c, --config <path>   - config file (default grpc-federation.yaml)
#   -w                    - watch mode: monitor proto files + regenerate
#                           interactively on change
#   -h, --help            - print help
#
# The wazero lane is built on `github.com/tetratelabs/wazero
# v1.10.1` (declared as a direct dep at upstream go.mod HEAD),
# the canonical Go WebAssembly runtime by Tetrate Labs
# (github.com/tetratelabs/wazero, 5300+ stars). wazero is the
# uncontested Go Wasm runtime - the *only* pure-Go Wasm
# runtime without CGo dependencies. The CGo-free design is
# the killer property for Go's cross-compile story: a Go
# binary that embeds wazero can be cross-compiled to every
# Go target (Linux/macOS/Windows on x86_64/arm64/riscv64)
# without per-target toolchain dependencies, in stark
# contrast to wasmer-go or wasmtime-go (CGo bindings that
# require platform-specific shared libraries).
#
# grpc-federation uses wazero to execute custom CEL
# (Common Expression Language) extensions written in Wasm -
# users can attach Wasm modules to federation messages to
# implement custom field-mapping logic that runs inside the
# generated server at request time.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 232 :: WebAssembly runtime + WASI host (Wasm spec + WASI Preview)
# Round 1395 :: Go slot 2 of 4 :: continues Axis 232
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : bytecodealliance/wasmtime    [R1394 _lunatic]
#   Go      : tetratelabs/wazero           [R1395 THIS FILE]
#   TS/Node : bytecodealliance/jco         [R1396 closing]
#
# wazero is structurally interesting in this axis: it is the
# *zero-dep* end of the runtime spectrum. wasmtime (Rust) is
# a heavyweight runtime with Cranelift JIT, multi-threaded
# epoch-based interruption, and full component-model support
# - the reference implementation that the Wasm spec uses as
# its conformance benchmark. wazero (Go) deliberately omits
# JIT (interpreter-only by default, optional Cranelift via
# wazero/experimental), keeps zero CGo dependencies, and
# trades execution speed for embeddability + cross-compile
# friendliness. The choice reflects Go's deployment story -
# Go programs ship as single static binaries to every
# platform Go supports; embedding a CGo-bound Wasm runtime
# would break that. wazero is the only way to have a Wasm
# runtime in a Go program without breaking it.
#
# Use-case alignment for Axis 232 across all three lanes:
#   - lunatic (Rust): full standalone Wasm runtime, Erlang-
#     inspired actor system on top of wasmtime
#   - grpc-federation-generator (Go): embed wazero in a code-
#     generation tool, run Wasm extensions at server runtime
#   - <Node slot> (closing): component-model interop tooling
#
# The cross-language Wasm interop story is total at the
# spec level - a Wasm module produced by `rustc --target
# wasm32-wasi` or `tinygo build -target wasi` runs identically
# under all three runtimes. The host integration differs.
# ============================================================================

_grpc-federation-generator() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '(-c --config)'{-c,--config}'[config path (default grpc-federation.yaml)]:file:_files -g "*.(yaml|yml)"' \
        '-w[watch mode: monitor proto files + regenerate]' \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print help]' \
        '1:proto file path:_files -g "*.proto"'
}

_grpc-federation-generator "$@"
